4/28/2026

Set up pfSense and created a segmented network with LAN and DMZ

What I did:

-Installed pfSense in VMware and assigned interfaces:
WAN (NAT)
LAN (VMnet1, 192.168.10.0/24)
DMZ (OPT1, VMnet2, 192.168.2.0/24)

-Connected machines to the network:
Kali (LAN)
Ubuntu (DMZ)
Wazuh VM (LAN)

-Troubleshot Kali connectivity issue:
Kali could not ping anything at first
Ran ip a, saw IP was assigned correctly
Ran ip route, noticed there was no default gateway, which means it could not reach the internet
Added gateway:
ip route add default via 192.168.10.1
After that, pinging started working

-Troubleshot Ubuntu DMZ connectivity issue:
Ubuntu could not reach other systems or communicate as expected
ping 192.168.2.1 (pfSense DMZ gateway) had no response
Checked ip a, IP was assigned correctly (192.168.2.x)
Checked ip route, verified default route existed
Still no communication
Looked into network config files under /etc/netplan and /etc/network
Made changes and reapplied configs:
sudo netplan apply
Also restarted networking multiple times, still no improvement
At this point confirmed IP was correct, routing was correct, and interface was up, so issue likely not on Ubuntu side
Shifted focus to pfSense firewall rules
Realized the allow dmz outbound rule source was set to OPT1 address instead of OPT1 subnet
Tried pinging again after implementing the fix, worked
Also configured block dmz to lan and allow dmz ping firewall rules
see dmz-firewall-rules.png in screenshots
Confirmed DMZ was blocked from LAN:
ping 192.168.10.x from Ubuntu had no response, rule works

-Troubleshot Kali losing connectivity to pfSense LAN gateway:
Kali could not ping 192.168.10.1, 100% packet loss
Checked ip a, IP still correct
Checked ip route, gateway still set
Checked ARP:
ip neigh
Saw 192.168.10.1 REACHABLE, so Layer 2 was working
Tried disabling firewall on pfSense
pfctl -d
No change, confirmed not a firewall issue
Restarted pfSense, ping worked again afterward
Noticed a pattern: pfSense stops working when starting or rebooting a VM on the network
Workaround: restart pfSense when this happens, will look into permanent fix

-Started setting static IPs to avoid DHCP issues

-Began setting up Wazuh:
Created new Ubuntu VM on LAN
Installed Wazuh using installer script
Got warning about UFW blocking ports
Disabled UFW temporarily:
sudo ufw disable
Finished install
Verified Wazuh dashboard accessible at https://192.168.10.x

What I learned:
-How to do basic network segmenting
-Default gateway is required for communication outside local network
-Difference between having an IP and having a route
-ARP showing REACHABLE means Layer 2 works but does not guarantee communication
-Basic router firewall configuration
-Using subnet vs interface address matters when creating rules
-How to test network behavior step by step: ip a, ip route, ping, ip neigh
-pfSense can stop responding when new VMs connect and may require a reboot
-Static IPs help avoid DHCP issues and inconsistent behavior in a lab environment
-Basic understanding of how SIEM (Wazuh) fits into a network
-Was really cool to see so much of what I learned in Network+ in action
